 "y0": 42.55, "x1": 90.81, "y1": 54.51}], "full_text": "Radiology\n2- Intra venous urography {IVU}\n• Contrast dye is injected IV, filtered by kidneys, then\nexcreted into urinary tract, allowing X-ray visualization\nof GUT.\n•Advantages\n- Visualize urinary tract lesions as filling defects\n(stones, tumors, blood clots, fungal balls, foreign bodies)\n- Back-pressure changes assessed\n- Inexpensive, available\n• Disadvantages\n- Ionizing radiation exposure\n- Contrast exposure\n- Need good kidney function\n- No assessment beyond obstruction\nIVU has 5 stages:\nIVU can detect:\n1- hydro-uretero-nephrosis\nDilated right pelvi-calyceal\nNormal pelvicalyceal system and upper ureter (hydro-\nsystem uretero-nephrosis)\n2- Ureters persistent filling defects\nUreters with fixed filling defects\n119"}